b:["$","p",null,{"className":"x:not-first:mt-[1.25em] x:leading-7","children":"Hard-coding domain names into the type system means every new integration requires a TypeScript type change. It leaks the assumption that workstacean always runs in the same environment with the same set of services. A team that runs workstacean against different infrastructure can’t add their own domains without forking the type."}]
c:["$","p",null,{"className":"x:not-first:mt-[1.25em] x:leading-7","children":[["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"WorldState = Record<string, unknown>"}]," removes this coupling entirely. Any domain can exist. Goals and actions reference domains by dot-path strings (",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"domains.my_service.data.value"}],"). The evaluator resolves these paths at evaluation time using a simple ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"get(obj, path)"}]," utility. The type system makes no promises about what domains exist — that’s a runtime configuration concern, not a compile-time concern."]}]
d:["$","p",null,{"className":"x:not-first:mt-[1.25em] x:leading-7","children":["The cost is that there’s no compile-time check that a ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"selector"}]," path is valid. The benefit is that the world engine works for any combination of HTTP endpoints, with zero code changes."]}]
